          "body": "The narrator's most important move is the placement of 9:15-17 — the prior divine disclosure — between Saul's arrival at the city (9:14) and his encounter with Samuel at the gate (9:18). The reader is given what Saul does not have. The LORD had spoken to Samuel the day before: 'About this time tomorrow I will send you a man from the land of Benjamin, and you shall anoint him to be *nagid* over My people Israel' (9:16). Three features of this oracle carry enormous weight. First, God is the one *sending* — Saul thinks he is looking for donkeys; God says He is sending a man. The subjects of the verbs disclose whose story this really is. Second, the title given is *nagid* (prince, designated leader) rather than *melek* (king) — a distinction the commentators note: *nagid* emphasizes appointment from above and accountability to God, not autonomous royal power (P. K. McCarter, *1 Samuel*, Anchor Bible, 1980). Third, the stated motive is compassion: 'I have regarded My people, because their cry has come to Me' (9:16). God chooses a king not because the request was legitimate — chapter 8 made clear it was not — but because He remains the shepherd of His people even when they choose poorly. The cry of the afflicted reaches God regardless of the institutional failure of those who afflict them."
