          "body": "The chapter ends at a threshold, not a resolution. Samuel and Saul descend from the high place, converse on the rooftop through the evening (9:25), rise early at dawn (9:26), and walk together to the edge of the city. There Samuel dismisses the servant: 'But you remain standing now, that I may proclaim the word of God to you' (9:27). The chapter closes without delivering that word. The anointing (10:1) and the cluster of signs (10:2-7) belong to the next chapter. This narrative restraint is itself a form of theology: the *word of God* is marked as so weighty that it requires private space (the servant sent ahead), a specific moment (dawn, at the city's edge), and total attention. The whole of chapter 9 — the failed search, the servant's suggestion, the women's directions, the reserved meal, the rooftop conversation — has been a long preparation for a word that has not yet been spoken. Howard Hendricks often said that the Bible's 'slow movements' are rarely wasted — they are the theological architecture of expectation."
