        "number": 3,
        "title": "The man who does not know he is the man — Saul's encounter with Samuel",
        "range": "9:18-21",
        "excerpt": "Then Saul approached Samuel in the gate and said, 'Please tell me where the seer's house is.' Samuel answered Saul and said, 'I am the seer.'",
        "body": "The encounter at the gate is constructed for maximum irony. Samuel has known Saul is coming for twenty-four hours, knows his name, his tribe, and his divine destiny. Saul does not know Samuel by sight and asks him for directions. The asymmetry of knowledge is total, and the narrator exploits it fully: the man designated to be the mouthpiece of God's word to the nation's future king is approached by that future king as a stranger who might give him walking directions.\n\nSamuel's response in verses 19-20 is a cascade of disclosures, each one larger than the last. First: 'I am the seer' — the person you seek is already in front of you. Second: 'Go up before me to the high place, for you shall eat with me today' — the invitation to a sacred meal is also an invitation into Samuel's prophetic orbit; you do not eat at the high place with the prophet as a casual guest. Third: 'I will tell you all that is on your mind' — a claim of prophetic sight that proves itself immediately when Samuel names the donkeys. Fourth: 'As for your donkeys which were lost three days ago, do not set your mind on them, for they have been found' — the minor question is closed so the major one can be opened. Fifth: 'For whom is all that is desirable in Israel? Is it not for you and for all your father's household?' — a cryptic elevation-hint whose full meaning Saul cannot yet decode.\n\nSaul's response in verse 21 is among the most theologically significant responses to divine election in the Old Testament: 'Am I not a Benjamite, of the smallest of the tribes of Israel, and my family the least of all the families of the tribe of Benjamin?' Two layers of minimization — tribal and familial — with a closing question: 'Why then do you speak to me in this way?' This is not false modesty performed for effect. Saul genuinely cannot map Samuel's hints onto his self-understanding. His self-knowledge is accurate as far as it goes: Benjamin was the smallest tribe, nearly annihilated in the civil war of Judges 19-21. His clan may indeed be least among Benjaminite clans. But self-knowledge, however accurate, is insufficient for understanding divine election — which is precisely the point. God's choices consistently confound human calculus of merit, size, and status (cf. 1 Corinthians 1:27-29, which is the New Testament articulation of this same principle).\n\nReformed exegetes from Calvin through Spurgeon have pressed the theological import of this moment: election is not based on the worthiness of the elected. God chooses Benjamin (the small tribe) for His first king exactly as He chose Benjamin's ancestor Jacob over Esau, as He chose Israel over the nations, as He will later choose David the youngest shepherd son. The pattern is consistent: the LORD does not choose whom the world would choose, and He consistently chooses in ways that make human boasting impossible."
